{"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift"]]},"variants":[{"paths":["\/documentation\/swift\/using-imported-c-structs-and-unions-in-swift"],"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}]}],"schemaVersion":{"patch":0,"major":0,"minor":3},"sections":[],"seeAlsoSections":[{"generated":true,"identifiers":["doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift\/customizing-your-c-code-for-swift","doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift\/using-imported-c-functions-in-swift","doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift\/using-imported-c-macros-in-swift"],"title":"Language Interoperability with C and C++","anchor":"Language-Interoperability-with-C-and-C++"}],"primaryContentSections":[{"content":[{"type":"heading","anchor":"Overview","level":2,"text":"Overview"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Swift imports any C structure declared in a C header as a Swift structure. The imported","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"Swift structure contains a stored property for each C structure field and an initializer","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"whose parameters correspond to the stored properties.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","anchor":"Structures-with-Default-Values","level":3,"text":"Structures with Default Values"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"If all imported members have default values, Swift also provides a default initializer","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"that takes no arguments. For example, given the following C structure:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"occ","code":["struct Color {","    float r, g, b;","};","typedef struct Color Color;"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"When you import the Color structure, the Swift version is equivalent to the following:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["public struct Color {","    var r: Float","    var g: Float","    var b: Float","","    init()","    init(r: Float, g: Float, b: Float)","}"]},{"type":"heading","anchor":"Unions","level":3,"text":"Unions"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Swift imports C unions as Swift structures. Although Swift doesn’t support natively","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"declared unions, a C union imported as a Swift structure still behaves like a C union.","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"For example, consider a C union named ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"SchroedingersCat"},{"text":" that has an ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"isAlive"},{"text":" and","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"an ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"isDead"},{"text":" field:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"occ","code":["union SchroedingersCat {","    bool isAlive;","    bool isDead;","};"]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In Swift, it’s imported like this:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["struct SchroedingersCat {","    var isAlive: Bool { get set }","    var isDead: Bool { get set }","","    init(isAlive: Bool)","    init(isDead: Bool)","","    init()","}"]},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Because unions in C use the same base memory address for all of their fields, all","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"of the computed properties in a union imported by Swift use the same underlying memory.","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"As a result, changing the value of a property on an instance of the imported structure","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"changes the value of all other properties defined by that structure.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In the example below, changing the value of the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"isAlive"},{"type":"text","text":" computed property on an"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"instance of the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"SchroedingersCat"},{"type":"text","text":" structure also changes the value of the instance’s"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"isDead"},{"type":"text","text":" computed property:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["var mittens = SchroedingersCat(isAlive: false)","","print(mittens.isAlive, mittens.isDead)","\/\/ Prints \"false false\"","","mittens.isAlive = true","print(mittens.isDead)","\/\/ Prints \"true\""]},{"anchor":"Bit-Fields","level":3,"type":"heading","text":"Bit Fields"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Swift imports bit fields that are declared in structures, like those found in Foundation’s","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"code":"NSDecimal","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" type, as computed properties. When accessing a computed property corresponding","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"to a bit field, Swift automatically converts the value to and from compatible Swift","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"types.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"anchor":"Unnamed-Structure-and-Union-Fields","level":3,"type":"heading","text":"Unnamed Structure and Union Fields"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"C "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"struct"},{"type":"text","text":" and "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"union"},{"type":"text","text":" types can define fields that have no name or that are of an"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"unnamed type. Unnamed fields consist of a nested "},{"code":"struct","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" or "},{"code":"union","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" type with named","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"fields.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"For example, consider a C structure named "},{"code":"Cake","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" that contains the fields "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"layers"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"and "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"height"},{"text":" nested within an unnamed union type, and a field ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"toppings"},{"type":"text","text":" of an unnamed"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"struct type:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"codeListing","code":["struct Cake {","    union {","        int layers;","        double height;","    };","","    struct {","        bool icing;","        bool sprinkles;","    } toppings;","};"],"syntax":"occ"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"After the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Cake"},{"type":"text","text":" structure has been imported, you can use the default initializer"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"to create an instance and use it as follows:","type":"text"}]},{"syntax":"swift","code":["var simpleCake = Cake()","simpleCake.layers = 5","print(simpleCake.toppings.icing)","\/\/ Prints \"false\""],"type":"codeListing"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The imported "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Cake"},{"type":"text","text":" structure and its nested types are imported with a memberwise"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"initializer that you can use to initialize the structure with custom values for its"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"fields:"}]},{"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing","code":["let cake = Cake(","    .init(layers: 2),","    toppings: .init(icing: true, sprinkles: false)",")","","print(\"The cake has \\(cake.layers) layers.\")","\/\/ Prints \"The cake has 2 layers.\"","print(\"Does it have sprinkles?\", cake.toppings.sprinkles ? \"Yes.\" : \"No.\")","\/\/ Prints \"Does it have sprinkles? No.\""]},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Because the first field of the ","type":"text"},{"code":"Cake","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" structure is unnamed, its initializer’s first","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"parameter doesn’t have a label. Because the ","type":"text"},{"code":"Cake","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" structure has fields with unnamed","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"types, you use the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":".init"},{"text":" initializers (allowed due to Swift’s type inference) to","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"set the initial value for each of the structure’s unnamed fields.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"kind":"content"}],"kind":"article","metadata":{"modules":[{"name":"Swift"}],"role":"article","title":"Using Imported C Structs and Unions in Swift","roleHeading":"Article"},"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift\/using-imported-c-structs-and-unions-in-swift","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"abstract":[{"text":"Learn how Swift represents imported C structures and unions, including types with","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"bitfields and unnamed fields.","type":"text"}],"references":{"doc://com.apple.Swift/documentation/Swift/customizing-your-c-code-for-swift":{"url":"\/documentation\/swift\/customizing-your-c-code-for-swift","role":"article","title":"Customizing Your C Code for Swift","type":"topic","kind":"article","identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift\/customizing-your-c-code-for-swift","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Use the "},{"code":"CF_SWIFT_NAME","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" macro to group functions that have related behavior.","type":"text"}]},"doc://com.apple.Swift/documentation/Swift/using-imported-c-macros-in-swift":{"role":"article","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Use imported C-defined macros as constants."}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift\/using-imported-c-macros-in-swift","title":"Using Imported C Macros in Swift","type":"topic","kind":"article","url":"\/documentation\/swift\/using-imported-c-macros-in-swift"},"doc://com.apple.Swift/documentation/Swift/using-imported-c-functions-in-swift":{"url":"\/documentation\/swift\/using-imported-c-functions-in-swift","type":"topic","kind":"article","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Learn how to call imported functions that are declared in a C header."}],"title":"Using Imported C Functions in Swift","role":"article","identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift\/using-imported-c-functions-in-swift"},"doc://com.apple.Swift/documentation/Swift":{"type":"topic","title":"Swift","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Build apps using a powerful open language."}],"kind":"symbol","url":"\/documentation\/swift","role":"collection","identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift"}}}